Analysis: I'd been relying on OurWorldInData as my data source as the Americas charts weren't showing up for me on the WHO link last time I checked. According to the WHO numbers now, we're at ~44M as of Jan 26th. This is lower than the 44.3M as of Jan 25th, that I'm seeing on OurWorldInData. Revising the calculations below, we'd need a doubling rate of <=13 weeks to see the total case count cross 46M[1]

Analysis: - We have seen a increase in total cases of +4M in 2 weeks from January 11th (my last estimate) to January 25th[1] - We have 1 week remaining and rate of increase is dropping in the Americas - To stay below 46M, with case count=44.3M on Jan 25th[1], we'd need the doubling rate to drop to 18.4 weeks[2] - To cross 48M, we'd need the doubling rate to increase to 8.6 weeks[3] - If we maintain our previous assumption of a doubling rate of 11 weeks, we expect to see 47.8M total cases - If we update our previous assumption and slow the doubling rate to 15 weeks, we expect to see 46.39M total cases by Feb 1st
Time for me to recognize the higher daily counts I’d anticipated are not coming in time to push the total above 46M by Feb 1.

I really, really want to jump on the <46M bandwagon, but I’m just not feeling it in my heart yet. This virus has gotten the better of the Americas region for a little over 365 days, and no amount of confidence in our abilities to reign it in will change that fact. Vaccinations are coming, but more slowly than expected. Behavioral change in this region is light years behind that of Asia and Europe. A slight breeze could shift the momentum enough to take us over 46M in a little over a week. I’ll be delighted if I’m wrong about this.

Process: 1. Model the case growth as an exponential. 2. Observe doubling rate of 11 weeks from 20M to 40M from October 27th - January 11th 3. For reference we see a doubling rate of 12.3 weeks and 5.14 weeks for the case count doubling before that respectively 4. Assuming doubling rate for next 3 months is at 10 weeks : 11 weeks : 12 weeks with odds 1 : 3 : 2 That is, assuming most probable doubling rate is the current doubling rate with a tilt towards faster spread than slower spread, we get expected value of 48.02 Million cases by Feb 1st 5. Spread the probability across all possible outcomes such that peak at >48M, a slight drop in next lower interval, and sharper drops for levels in subsequent lower intervals References: - Data Source: https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus-data-explorer?zoomToSelection=true&time=2020-03-01..2021-01-11&country=NorthAmerica~SouthAmerica&region=World&casesMetric=true&interval=total&smoothing=0&pickerMetric=total_cases&pickerSort=desc - Exponentiation Doubling Rate: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doubling_time#Cell_culture_doubling_time

I took a relatively simple approach since I wasn't able to find weekly data in a CSV file quickly and could only find WHO data for the past week. Looking at the current WHO data, there are 38,861,668 cases in the Americas. The average of the weekly increase of each country in the Americas is 6.6% for the past week. Without data on how much a vaccine would potentially reduce cases of COVID, I applied a 6.6% increase weekly for the next 3 weeks and got around 47 million cases in the Americas. By comparing this against the weekly charts on the website, it looks like the Americas have experienced about a 2-2.5 million case increase weekly, over the next three weeks that would mean 6-8 million additional cases.

Looking at flu trends for the Americas for the past 4 years between weeks 1 and 5 presents an average of 61% increases in flu cases. The vaccine is rolling out in North America (53% of the Americas population) although only to a limited, most at-risk portion of the populations thus far. Therefore assuming around a 75% increase in cases reported from week 1 to week 5 of 2021. The vaccine is only rolling out in Central and South America (47% of the population) in a very few countries and therefore I'm assuming a much higher increase of 90% in cases reported from week 1 to week 5 of 2021. I've not seen any changes in reporting techniques in the Americas for the WHO website. Taking into account the week 1 total for the Americas of 2,522,297 cases and multiplying by the aforementioned percentages weighted for population, I'm estimating a total of 43M cases on 01-Feb. If I'm off, it's likely too low, and therefore I'm giving a high probability to 44-46M as well.

Forecast being done on 1/9. 23 days left to add to case counts. Outside view: According to the WHO dashboard, right now there are 40.76 million cases in the Americas. New cases reported in the last 24 hours is 441,576. The US has the preponderance, WHO reported 277195 yesterday. The CDC 7 day rolling average is 248K new cases in the US (country w/ largest impact on americas), with the trend continuing to spike. At 23 days times 441K cases, that’s an extra 10 million cases on Feb 1 after the Jan 31 cases are accounted for. That brings the total to 50.76 million. Even if the US amounts are not at a rate of 277K per day (CDC count is higher at 314K) and are instead at the 7 day rolling average, that only eliminates ~690K cases. Inside view: The vaccine rollout has been slow, effects are still happening from holiday travel, and the B1.1.7 mutation is just starting to get going in the USA. It is the beginning of winter and people are going to be indoors. No major changes in preventive measures. (Although there could possibly be after the inauguration, but best case that wouldn’t have an effect until past 1 Feb). The trend line gives me no reason to believe that the 7 day average will even level off, let alone subside. No major breakthroughs on the horizon. Based on these factors, my estimate is 97% confidence that the Americas total is above 48 million, 3% confidence that it’s between 46-48 mil.

According to Our World in Data, the combined number for North + South America today is 39 million confirmed cases. Whereas North America is fluctuating quite wildly, the curve for South America appears more stable. Importantly, the more transmissible variant b.1.1.7 has only recently been confirmed in Colorado, California, Florida and New York. It is quite likely that the variant has reached both North/South America regions, given it was discovered in Kent/London as early as September. However, while it is likely to be present, the extent to which is contributing to spread is unclear. All other things equal, the inveitable introduction or continued spread of the more transmissible variant is likely to increase cases at a higher rate than what is currently seen. So what rate of confirmed cases are we currently seeing?

Coming off of weekend and holiday low reporting periods, we have seen that the case numbers are steadily rising in the U.S. again. I do not expect this to slow down in the next few weeks since those that were exposed during the holidays will start getting sick right about now. With quarantine fatigue and the unlikely potential for shutdowns effecting the numbers for several weeks even if implemented today, I do not see this being anything less than the current weekly average of 306,443.571 cases per day. At this average, we would be in the 44,000,000-46,000,000 bin by 1 Feb (306,443.571*24=7,354,645.704+37,538,493=44,893,138.704). However, today’s numbers are probably more telling, as we have reached 348,951 cases and the reporting period is still not over. I can easily see the numbers in the U.S. getting up to around 270,000-300,000 cases a day on its own. The U.S. had 260,937 cases reported yesterday according to a source other than the WHO, who is a little bit slower at increasing numbers. However, the U.S. is at 227,369 today according to the WHO. The other site I used has a similar number for two days ago, at 234,711. I expect tomorrow’s WHO numbers for the U.S. will likely be somewhere between 240,000 and 260,000, and the total for the Americas will also likely go up significantly. There are always dips in the numbers over the weekends, so I expect that the average will stay somewhere in Bin 4 for now, but we will see as the next few days show us what is happening after the holiday family gatherings.

Naïve initial forecast - only looking at the daily/weekly cases, extrapolating, then assuming (perhaps optimistically) that, at least in the US, folks were more likely to get exposed to the virus between Thanksgiving and New Years. I suspect we'll see higher numbers in early January (carryover from Xmas and NYE exposures) with it tapering slightly as the month progresses - leaving a lower total new cases than we saw in December.

The buffer to the up-side of approx. 50,000 cases per day leaves room even for a possible second wave (c) in Peru. If all four (a)+(b)+(c)+(d) coincide, it may become necessary to overweight bin 4 "Between 46,000,000 and 48,000,000, inclusive".
